Note:
SQL NUMERIC(p, s) - Exact decimal arithmetic per SQL standard.

This is distinct from IEEE 754 Decimal128 (which has a fixed exponent
range and binary-encoded digits). SQL NUMERIC stores:
  - precision p: total number of significant decimal digits (1..1000)
  - scale s: number of digits to the right of the decimal point (0..p)
  - sign: 0 = positive, 1 = negative
  - digit stream: little-endian base-10 digits (one digit per byte)

This implementation mirrors PostgreSQL NUMERIC, MySQL DECIMAL, and SQL
Server DECIMAL semantics for arithmetic, rounding, and precision
overflow.

SQLNumeric layout (40 bytes):
  offset 0:  precision (8 bytes)
  offset 8:  scale     (8 bytes)
  offset 16: sign      (8 bytes)
  offset 24: digit_count (8 bytes)
  offset 32: digit_buffer_ptr (8 bytes) - little-endian base-10 digits

Dependencies:
- numeric/decimal/decimal_bignum.runa (raw bignum ops)
- memory/layout.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/numeric/decimal/decimal_bignum.runa" as DecBN
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Mem
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/char_core.runa" as Char

Constant SN_OFF_PRECISION as Integer is 0
Constant SN_OFF_SCALE as Integer is 8
Constant SN_OFF_SIGN as Integer is 16
Constant SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT as Integer is 24
Constant SN_OFF_DIGITS as Integer is 32
Constant SN_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 40

Constant SN_OK as Integer is 1
Constant SN_ERR_INVALID as Integer is 0
Constant SN_ERR_OVERFLOW as Integer is -1
Constant SN_ERR_DIV_ZERO as Integer is -2

Constant SN_MAX_PRECISION as Integer is 1000

Constant ROUND_HALF_EVEN as Integer is 0
Constant ROUND_HALF_UP as Integer is 1
Constant ROUND_TRUNCATE as Integer is 2

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Construction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Construct a SQLNumeric record. Allocates the digit buffer separately to
allow precision changes via reallocation in later phases.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate the 40-byte record, allocate a digit buffer of `precision` bytes
(one base-10 digit per byte), zero the digits, store fields.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two allocs. Reuse via sqlnum_assign for hot loops.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
precision must be in 1..SN_MAX_PRECISION, scale must be in 0..precision.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_create" takes precision as Integer, scale as Integer returns Integer:
    If precision is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If precision is greater than SN_MAX_PRECISION:
        Return 0
    End If
    If scale is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If scale is greater than precision:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let n be proc allocate from Memory with SN_STRUCT_SIZE
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let digits be proc allocate from Memory with precision
    If digits is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with n
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Zero-fill digit buffer
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than precision:
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with digits, i, 0
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_PRECISION, precision
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SCALE, scale
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SIGN, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGITS, digits
    Return n
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_destroy" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return SN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    If digits is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with digits
    End If
    proc deallocate from Memory with n
    Return SN_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "sqlnum_precision" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_PRECISION
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_scale" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SCALE
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_sign" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SIGN
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_digit_count" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_is_zero" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let dc be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    If dc is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Integer construction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Build a SQLNumeric from a signed integer value. The scale is preserved
(value is interpreted as the unscaled coefficient).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Take absolute value of input, write decimal digits little-endian into the
buffer up to precision, set sign and digit_count.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(digit_count).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must ensure the integer fits in `precision` digits after scaling.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_from_integer" takes precision as Integer, scale as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Let n be proc sqlnum_create with precision, scale
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sign be 0
    Let mag be value
    If mag is less than 0:
        Set sign to 1
        Set mag to (0 minus mag)
    End If

    Let digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let count be 0
    While mag is not equal to 0:
        If count is greater than or equal to precision:
            proc sqlnum_destroy with n
            Return 0
        End If
        Let d be mag minus ((mag divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with digits, count, d
        Set mag to (mag divided by 10)
        Set count to count plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SIGN, sign
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT, count
    Return n
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parse from string
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Parse a decimal string of the form "[-+]?[0-9]+(\.[0-9]+)?" into a
SQLNumeric. Scale is taken from the post-decimal-point digit count.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Skip leading whitespace, read optional sign, read integer digits, read
optional fractional digits, count scale = number of fractional digits.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(string length).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
str_ptr must be a valid null-terminated byte string.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_string_length" takes str_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let n be 0
    Let cur be 0
    Let polling be 1
    While polling is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with str_ptr, n
        If c is equal to 0:
            Set polling to 0
        Otherwise:
            Set n to n plus 1
        End If
        Note: Hard cap to prevent infinite loop on missing terminator
        If n is greater than 65536:
            Set polling to 0
        End If
    End While
    Return n
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_from_string" takes str_ptr as Integer, max_precision as Integer returns Integer:
    If str_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let len be proc sqlnum_string_length with str_ptr
    Let i be 0

    Note: Skip whitespace
    Let polling be 1
    While polling is equal to 1:
        If i is greater than or equal to len:
            Set polling to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let c be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with str_ptr, i
            Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace from Char with c
            If is_ws is equal to 0:
                Set polling to 0
            Otherwise:
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let sign be 0
    If i is less than len:
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with str_ptr, i
        If c2 is equal to 45:
            Set sign to 1
            Set i to i plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If c2 is equal to 43:
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Collect integer digits and fractional digits into a temp buffer
    Let temp_digits be proc allocate from Memory with max_precision
    If temp_digits is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let total_digits be 0
    Let scale_found be 0
    Let saw_dot be 0

    Let parsing be 1
    While parsing is equal to 1:
        If i is greater than or equal to len:
            Set parsing to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let c3 be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with str_ptr, i
            Let is_d be proc is_digit from Char with c3
            If is_d is equal to 1:
                If total_digits is greater than or equal to max_precision:
                    proc deallocate from Memory with temp_digits
                    Return 0
                End If
                Let digit_val be c3 minus 48
                proc memory_set_byte from Mem with temp_digits, total_digits, digit_val
                Set total_digits to total_digits plus 1
                If saw_dot is equal to 1:
                    Set scale_found to scale_found plus 1
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            Otherwise:
                If c3 is equal to 46:
                    If saw_dot is equal to 1:
                        proc deallocate from Memory with temp_digits
                        Return 0
                    End If
                    Set saw_dot to 1
                    Set i to i plus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Set parsing to 0
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    If total_digits is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with temp_digits
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Determine precision (use total_digits since leading zeros are kept)
    Let n be proc sqlnum_create with max_precision, scale_found
    If n is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with temp_digits
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: temp_digits is big-endian (most-significant first). Reverse into
    Note: the SQLNumeric's little-endian digit buffer.
    Let dest_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let src_i be 0
    While src_i is less than total_digits:
        Let dest_i be (total_digits minus 1) minus src_i
        Let d4 be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with temp_digits, src_i
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with dest_digits, dest_i, d4
        Set src_i to src_i plus 1
    End While
    proc deallocate from Memory with temp_digits

    Note: Trim leading zeros in the high digits to compute digit_count
    Let dc be total_digits
    Let trimming be 1
    While trimming is equal to 1:
        If dc is less than or equal to 0:
            Set trimming to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let dh be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with dest_digits, (dc minus 1)
            If dh is equal to 0:
                Set dc to dc minus 1
            Otherwise:
                Set trimming to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SIGN, sign
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT, dc
    Return n
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Equality / comparison
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Compare two SQLNumerics for ordering. Returns negative, zero, or positive.
Aligns scales by virtually padding the smaller-scale value with trailing
zero digits, then compares signed digit streams.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Match scales by computing aligned digit counts, compare sign first, then
compare magnitudes after virtual alignment.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(max(digit_count_a, digit_count_b)).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure comparison; safe.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_compare_aligned_magnitudes" takes a_digits as Integer, a_count as Integer, a_scale as Integer, b_digits as Integer, b_count as Integer, b_scale as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert each to a "shifted digit index" relative to max_scale
    Let max_scale be a_scale
    If b_scale is greater than max_scale:
        Set max_scale to b_scale
    End If
    Let a_shift be max_scale minus a_scale
    Let b_shift be max_scale minus b_scale
    Let a_eff_count be a_count plus a_shift
    Let b_eff_count be b_count plus b_shift

    If a_eff_count is greater than b_eff_count:
        Return 1
    End If
    If b_eff_count is greater than a_eff_count:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: Same effective count: compare digit-by-digit from high to low
    Let i be a_eff_count minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let a_real_idx be i minus a_shift
        Let b_real_idx be i minus b_shift
        Let av be 0
        Let bv be 0
        If a_real_idx is greater than or equal to 0:
            If a_real_idx is less than a_count:
                Set av to proc memory_get_byte from Mem with a_digits, a_real_idx
            End If
        End If
        If b_real_idx is greater than or equal to 0:
            If b_real_idx is less than b_count:
                Set bv to proc memory_get_byte from Mem with b_digits, b_real_idx
            End If
        End If
        If av is greater than bv:
            Return 1
        End If
        If bv is greater than av:
            Return -1
        End If
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_compare" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let a_is_zero be proc sqlnum_is_zero with a
    Let b_is_zero be proc sqlnum_is_zero with b
    If a_is_zero is equal to 1:
        If b_is_zero is equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let bs be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SIGN
        If bs is equal to 0:
            Return -1
        End If
        Return 1
    End If
    If b_is_zero is equal to 1:
        Let as_ be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_SIGN
        If as_ is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        Return -1
    End If

    Let a_sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_SIGN
    Let b_sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SIGN

    If a_sign is not equal to b_sign:
        If a_sign is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        Return -1
    End If

    Let a_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let a_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let a_scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let b_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let b_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let b_scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SCALE

    Let mag_cmp be proc sqlnum_compare_aligned_magnitudes with a_digits, a_count, a_scale, b_digits, b_count, b_scale
    If a_sign is equal to 1:
        Note: Both negative; invert magnitude comparison
        Return 0 minus mag_cmp
    End If
    Return mag_cmp
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_equals" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let c be proc sqlnum_compare with a, b
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Addition / subtraction (magnitude-aligned)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Add two SQLNumerics. Aligns scales, performs base-10 magnitude add with
carry. Handles sign by delegating to subtract when signs differ.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Align scales by padding the lower-scale operand's digit stream. Walk both
streams from low to high, summing digits with carry. Result scale =
max(a.scale, b.scale). Precision = max(a.prec, b.prec) + 1 to accommodate
carry-out (caller may round back down via sqlnum_rescale).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(max(digit_count)).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returned value must be released via sqlnum_destroy.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_aligned_get_digit" takes digits as Integer, count as Integer, shift as Integer, i as Integer returns Integer:
    Let real_idx be i minus shift
    If real_idx is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If real_idx is greater than or equal to count:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, real_idx
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let a_sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_SIGN
    Let b_sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SIGN

    Note: If signs differ, delegate to subtraction logic
    If a_sign is not equal to b_sign:
        Return proc sqlnum_signed_combine with a, b, 1
    End If

    Let a_scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let b_scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let max_scale be a_scale
    If b_scale is greater than max_scale:
        Set max_scale to b_scale
    End If

    Let a_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let b_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let a_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let b_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let a_shift be max_scale minus a_scale
    Let b_shift be max_scale minus b_scale
    Let a_eff be a_count plus a_shift
    Let b_eff be b_count plus b_shift
    Let max_eff be a_eff
    If b_eff is greater than max_eff:
        Set max_eff to b_eff
    End If
    Let result_prec be max_eff plus 1
    If result_prec is greater than SN_MAX_PRECISION:
        Set result_prec to SN_MAX_PRECISION
    End If

    Let r be proc sqlnum_create with result_prec, max_scale
    If r is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let r_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with r, SN_OFF_DIGITS

    Let carry be 0
    Let i be 0
    Let written be 0
    While i is less than max_eff:
        Let ad be proc sqlnum_aligned_get_digit with a_digits, a_count, a_shift, i
        Let bd be proc sqlnum_aligned_get_digit with b_digits, b_count, b_shift, i
        Let sum be ad plus bd plus carry
        Let d be sum minus ((sum divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
        Set carry to (sum divided by 10)
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with r_digits, i, d
        Set i to i plus 1
        If d is not equal to 0:
            Set written to (i)
        End If
    End While
    If carry is greater than 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with r_digits, i, carry
        Set written to (i plus 1)
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with r, SN_OFF_SIGN, a_sign
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with r, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT, written
    Return r
End Process

@Reasoning
Internal signed combine: subtract the smaller-magnitude operand from the
larger and take the sign of the larger. Used by add (for mixed-sign) and
sub.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Determine the larger magnitude, subtract digit-by-digit with borrow,
produce the result with the larger's sign.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(max_eff).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper - caller passes inputs already typed-checked.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_signed_combine" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, op_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Let a_sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_SIGN
    Let b_sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SIGN
    Note: op_mode reserved for future expansion; treat as add-with-mixed-signs

    Let a_scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let b_scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let max_scale be a_scale
    If b_scale is greater than max_scale:
        Set max_scale to b_scale
    End If

    Let a_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let b_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let a_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let b_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_DIGITS

    Let mag_cmp be proc sqlnum_compare_aligned_magnitudes with a_digits, a_count, a_scale, b_digits, b_count, b_scale

    Let larger be a
    Let smaller be b
    Let result_sign be a_sign
    If mag_cmp is less than 0:
        Set larger to b
        Set smaller to a
        Set result_sign to b_sign
    End If
    If mag_cmp is equal to 0:
        Let zero be proc sqlnum_create with 1, 0
        Return zero
    End If

    Let lc be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with larger, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let sc be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with smaller, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let ld be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with larger, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let sd be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with smaller, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let lsc be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with larger, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let ssc be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with smaller, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let l_shift be max_scale minus lsc
    Let s_shift be max_scale minus ssc
    Let l_eff be lc plus l_shift
    Let s_eff be sc plus s_shift
    Let max_eff be l_eff
    If s_eff is greater than max_eff:
        Set max_eff to s_eff
    End If

    Let r be proc sqlnum_create with max_eff, max_scale
    If r is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let r_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with r, SN_OFF_DIGITS

    Let borrow be 0
    Let i be 0
    Let last_nonzero be 0
    While i is less than max_eff:
        Let lv be proc sqlnum_aligned_get_digit with ld, lc, l_shift, i
        Let sv be proc sqlnum_aligned_get_digit with sd, sc, s_shift, i
        Let diff be lv minus sv minus borrow
        If diff is less than 0:
            Set diff to diff plus 10
            Set borrow to 1
        Otherwise:
            Set borrow to 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with r_digits, i, diff
        If diff is not equal to 0:
            Set last_nonzero to (i plus 1)
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with r, SN_OFF_SIGN, result_sign
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with r, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT, last_nonzero
    Return r
End Process

@Reasoning
Subtract: a - b is equivalent to a + (-b). Flip b's sign and dispatch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Clone b (or temporarily flip its sign in-place and restore).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Same as add.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The temporary sign flip is reversed before return; b is unchanged from
caller's perspective.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_sub" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let original_sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SIGN
    Let flipped be 1
    If original_sign is equal to 1:
        Set flipped to 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SIGN, flipped
    Let r be proc sqlnum_add with a, b
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SIGN, original_sign
    Return r
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Multiplication
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Multiply two SQLNumerics. Result precision = a.prec + b.prec; result
scale = a.scale + b.scale. Sign = XOR of signs (negative if exactly one
is negative).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Schoolbook digit multiplication: for each pair of digits accumulate into
the result buffer at the appropriate offset, propagating carry.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(a.digit_count * b.digit_count). Use sqlnum_rescale to trim.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returned value must be released.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_mul" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let b_scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let a_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let b_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let a_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let b_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_DIGITS
    Let a_sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with a, SN_OFF_SIGN
    Let b_sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with b, SN_OFF_SIGN

    Let result_scale be a_scale plus b_scale
    Let result_prec be a_count plus b_count plus 1
    If result_prec is less than (result_scale plus 1):
        Set result_prec to result_scale plus 1
    End If
    If result_prec is greater than SN_MAX_PRECISION:
        Set result_prec to SN_MAX_PRECISION
    End If

    Let r be proc sqlnum_create with result_prec, result_scale
    If r is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let r_digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with r, SN_OFF_DIGITS

    Let i be 0
    Let max_pos be 0
    While i is less than a_count:
        Let carry be 0
        Let ai be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with a_digits, i
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than b_count:
            Let bi be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with b_digits, j
            Let pos be i plus j
            If pos is greater than or equal to result_prec:
                Set j to b_count
            Otherwise:
                Let existing be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with r_digits, pos
                Let prod be ((ai multiplied by bi) plus existing) plus carry
                Let d be prod minus ((prod divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
                Set carry to (prod divided by 10)
                proc memory_set_byte from Mem with r_digits, pos, d
                If d is not equal to 0:
                    If (pos plus 1) is greater than max_pos:
                        Set max_pos to (pos plus 1)
                    End If
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End If
        End While
        Note: Propagate remaining carry
        Let cpos be i plus b_count
        While carry is greater than 0:
            If cpos is greater than or equal to result_prec:
                Set carry to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let ce be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with r_digits, cpos
                Let csum be ce plus carry
                Let cd be csum minus ((csum divided by 10) multiplied by 10)
                Set carry to (csum divided by 10)
                proc memory_set_byte from Mem with r_digits, cpos, cd
                If cd is not equal to 0:
                    If (cpos plus 1) is greater than max_pos:
                        Set max_pos to (cpos plus 1)
                    End If
                End If
                Set cpos to cpos plus 1
            End If
        End While
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let r_sign be 0
    If a_sign is not equal to b_sign:
        Set r_sign to 1
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with r, SN_OFF_SIGN, r_sign
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with r, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT, max_pos
    Return r
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Negate / absolute
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "sqlnum_negate_in_place" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return SN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let s be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SIGN
    Let flipped be 1
    If s is equal to 1:
        Set flipped to 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SIGN, flipped
    Return SN_OK
End Process

Process called "sqlnum_abs_in_place" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return SN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SIGN, 0
    Return SN_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Truncate / round
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Rescale a SQLNumeric to a target scale. Rounding mode controls how
fractional digits below the new scale are handled.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
If new_scale >= current_scale, pad zero digits at the low end (shift
digits up). If new_scale < current_scale, drop the lowest digits applying
the rounding mode.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(digit_count) in either direction.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Mutates the SQLNumeric in place.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_rescale_in_place" takes n as Integer, new_scale as Integer, rounding_mode as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return SN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If new_scale is less than 0:
        Return SN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let cur_scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let precision be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_PRECISION
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGITS

    If new_scale is equal to cur_scale:
        Return SN_OK
    End If

    If new_scale is greater than cur_scale:
        Let shift_up be new_scale minus cur_scale
        Let new_count be count plus shift_up
        If new_count is greater than precision:
            Return SN_ERR_OVERFLOW
        End If
        Note: Shift digits up by `shift_up` positions; zero-fill low end
        Let k be count minus 1
        While k is greater than or equal to 0:
            Let d be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, k
            proc memory_set_byte from Mem with digits, (k plus shift_up), d
            Set k to k minus 1
        End While
        Let z be 0
        While z is less than shift_up:
            proc memory_set_byte from Mem with digits, z, 0
            Set z to z plus 1
        End While
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT, new_count
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SCALE, new_scale
        Return SN_OK
    End If

    Note: new_scale < cur_scale: drop low digits with rounding
    Let drop_count be cur_scale minus new_scale
    Let round_digit be 0
    If drop_count is less than or equal to count:
        Set round_digit to proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, (drop_count minus 1)
    End If
    Note: ROUND_TRUNCATE drops everything. ROUND_HALF_UP rounds 5+ up.
    Note: ROUND_HALF_EVEN: 5 followed by zeros rounds to even, else like HALF_UP.

    Let do_round_up be 0
    If rounding_mode is equal to ROUND_HALF_UP:
        If round_digit is greater than or equal to 5:
            Set do_round_up to 1
        End If
    End If
    If rounding_mode is equal to ROUND_HALF_EVEN:
        If round_digit is greater than 5:
            Set do_round_up to 1
        Otherwise:
            If round_digit is equal to 5:
                Note: Check if any digit below is nonzero
                Let any_nonzero be 0
                Let k2 be 0
                While k2 is less than (drop_count minus 1):
                    Let d2 be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, k2
                    If d2 is not equal to 0:
                        Set any_nonzero to 1
                    End If
                    Set k2 to k2 plus 1
                End While
                If any_nonzero is equal to 1:
                    Set do_round_up to 1
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Tie: round to even (next digit even = round down)
                    Let next_digit be 0
                    If drop_count is less than count:
                        Set next_digit to proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, drop_count
                    End If
                    Let is_odd be next_digit minus ((next_digit divided by 2) multiplied by 2)
                    If is_odd is equal to 1:
                        Set do_round_up to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Shift digits down
    Let new_count2 be count minus drop_count
    If new_count2 is less than 0:
        Set new_count2 to 0
    End If
    Let m be 0
    While m is less than new_count2:
        Let dm be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, (m plus drop_count)
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with digits, m, dm
        Set m to m plus 1
    End While
    Note: Zero the now-unused high positions
    Let z2 be new_count2
    While z2 is less than count:
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with digits, z2, 0
        Set z2 to z2 plus 1
    End While

    If do_round_up is equal to 1:
        Note: Add 1 to digit[0], propagating carry
        Let carry be 1
        Let p be 0
        While carry is greater than 0:
            If p is greater than or equal to precision:
                Set carry to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let dv be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, p
                Let nv be dv plus carry
                If nv is greater than or equal to 10:
                    proc memory_set_byte from Mem with digits, p, (nv minus 10)
                    Set carry to 1
                Otherwise:
                    proc memory_set_byte from Mem with digits, p, nv
                    Set carry to 0
                End If
                Set p to p plus 1
                If p is greater than new_count2:
                    Set new_count2 to p
                End If
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Note: Recompute digit_count by trimming leading zeros
    Let trim be new_count2
    Let trimming be 1
    While trimming is equal to 1:
        If trim is less than or equal to 0:
            Set trimming to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let dh be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, (trim minus 1)
            If dh is equal to 0:
                Set trim to trim minus 1
            Otherwise:
                Set trimming to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT, trim
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SCALE, new_scale
    Return SN_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Serialization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Render to a decimal string. Writes into a caller-provided buffer of size
out_buf_size and returns the number of bytes written (excluding null
terminator). If the buffer is too small returns -1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walk digits high-to-low, writing ASCII characters. Inject the decimal
point at position `digit_count - scale`. Prepend '-' for negative.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(digit_count) string write.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
out_buf must be writable for at least out_buf_size bytes.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sqlnum_to_string" takes n as Integer, out_buf as Integer, out_buf_size as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If out_buf is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let sign be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SIGN
    Let scale be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_SCALE
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGIT_COUNT
    Let digits be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with n, SN_OFF_DIGITS

    If count is equal to 0:
        Note: Zero - emit "0" with optional scale
        If out_buf_size is less than 2:
            Return -1
        End If
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with out_buf, 0, 48
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with out_buf, 1, 0
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Compute needed length:
    Note:   sign (1) + integer_part + dot (1) + fractional_part
    Let int_part_count be count minus scale
    If int_part_count is less than 1:
        Set int_part_count to 1
    End If
    Let frac_count be scale
    Let total_len be int_part_count
    If sign is equal to 1:
        Set total_len to total_len plus 1
    End If
    If frac_count is greater than 0:
        Set total_len to total_len plus 1 plus frac_count
    End If

    If total_len plus 1 is greater than out_buf_size:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let pos be 0
    If sign is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with out_buf, pos, 45
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End If

    Note: Integer part: digits at indices [scale .. count-1] in little-endian
    Let i be count minus 1
    Let any_emitted be 0
    While i is greater than or equal to scale:
        Let d be proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, i
        If any_emitted is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_byte from Mem with out_buf, pos, (d plus 48)
            Set pos to pos plus 1
        Otherwise:
            If d is not equal to 0:
                proc memory_set_byte from Mem with out_buf, pos, (d plus 48)
                Set pos to pos plus 1
                Set any_emitted to 1
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While
    If any_emitted is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with out_buf, pos, 48
        Set pos to pos plus 1
    End If

    If frac_count is greater than 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Mem with out_buf, pos, 46
        Set pos to pos plus 1
        Let j be scale minus 1
        While j is greater than or equal to 0:
            Let d2 be 0
            If j is less than count:
                Set d2 to proc memory_get_byte from Mem with digits, j
            End If
            proc memory_set_byte from Mem with out_buf, pos, (d2 plus 48)
            Set pos to pos plus 1
            Set j to j minus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc memory_set_byte from Mem with out_buf, pos, 0
    Return pos
End Process
